## 2. When is a technique actually *detected*? (DNF firing semantics)

A rule does not watch a flat list of operations — it fires on a **boolean condition**. If a
rule requires calls B **and** C **and** D, a technique performing only B and C must **not**
count as detected: the rule never fires. So each rule carries its firing condition in
**disjunctive normal form** (`detection/record.py`):

- **groups** are ORed — the rule fires if *any* group is satisfied;
- **ops within a group** are ANDed — a group is satisfied only if *every* op occurs;
- **each op** is itself a disjunction of the permissions that realise it.

Rule *R* detects technique *T* iff there exists a group *G* in *R* such that **for every op in
*G***: (a) some permission of the op is required by *T* (**coverage**), and (b) some such
permission is **logged by default** (**visibility**).

Matching is not enough — the operation also has to be **written to a log that is on by
default**. GCP Cloud Audit Logs split into two tiers, and Google fixes the tier by the
permission's *type* (`detection/logtype.py`, authoritative from the curated table where
known, verb-heuristic otherwise):

| Log tier | What lands here | Default |
|---|---|---|
| **Admin Activity** | config / IAM / metadata **writes** (`ADMIN_WRITE`) | **always on** — a rule can see it |
| **Data Access** | reads, token minting, KMS decrypt, object/secret payloads (`ADMIN_READ`/`DATA_*`) | **off by default** — a rule never receives the event |

So every technique falls into exactly one bucket:

| `blind_class` | Meaning | Remedy |
|---|---|---|
| `DETECTED` | a single-event rule fires on it (a group satisfied on a logged op) | — |
| `CORRELATION_ONLY` | only a **threshold / multi-stage** rule fires — needs repetition or a full chain; one careful execution stays silent | tune thresholds / correlate |
| `RULE_GAP` (A) | an operation **is** logged, but **no rule** fires | write a signature — the evidence is already in the logs |
| `TELEMETRY_GAP` (B) | every observable operation is Data Access, **off by default** | *no signature can ever fire* until logging is reconfigured |

The load-bearing distinction remains: **`logged` ≠ `detected`.** A `DETECTED_BY` edge is
derived only when a rule *group* is fully satisfied on operations that are *also*
logged-by-default — the honest definition of "a signature would actually fire in a stock
project."

