## 5. Graph schema

```mermaid
flowchart LR
  T[Technique] -->|REQUIRES optional?| P[Permission]
  R[DetectionRule] -->|WATCHES op_token| P
  R -->|HAS_GROUP| G[RuleGroup]
  G -->|NEEDS| P
  T -->|"DETECTED_BY paradigm,threshold"| R
  T -->|GRANTS| C[Capability]
  C -->|IMPLIES| C
  C -->|UNLOCKS| T
  T -->|ENABLES| T
  T -->|IN_TACTIC| TA[Tactic]
  T -->|FOR_SERVICE| S[Service]
```

- **`Permission`** carries `log_type` (`ADMIN_ACTIVITY`/`DATA_ACCESS`), `logged_by_default`
  and `log_source` (`official` when the tier came from the curated table, else `heuristic`).
- **`DetectionRule`** carries `source` (sigma/elastic/gsecops/panther), `paradigm`, `threshold`,
  `window`, `domain`. Ids are namespaced (`sigma:…`, `panther:…`) so the Sigma-only baseline is
  reproducible by `WHERE r.source = 'sigma'`.
- **`RuleGroup`** materialises **conjunctive** groups only (size ≥ 2), so a B+C+D requirement —
  e.g. the Panther `run.services.create` **and** `run.services.setIamPolicy` chain — is
  explicit in the graph rather than hidden in the rule text.
- **`DETECTED_BY`** and **`ENABLES`** are *derived* at build time; `WATCHES` is a flat
  convenience edge (union of a rule's op permissions); everything else is extracted.
- **Workspace / UEBA rules** contribute no operation, so they exist as nodes but create no
  coverage.

