## 6. Reference data & provenance

The permission dialect gap is bridged by pinned reference tables under `data/reference/`
(regenerated by `python -m reference.fetch_reference`; see `data/reference/PROVENANCE.md`):

| File | Source | Kind |
|---|---|---|
| `method_permissions.json` | [`iann0036/iam-dataset`](https://github.com/iann0036/iam-dataset) `gcp/map.json`, commit-pinned | community, machine-readable (6072 methods) |
| `permissions.json` | same repo, canonical permission vocabulary | community, machine-readable (10129 permissions) |
| `reference/rpc_methods.json` | Google's official per-service audit-logging docs, hand-transcribed with a per-entry `source` | **official** (~25 gRPC methods) |

Google publishes the method→permission mapping only as prose tables on ~180 per-service HTML
pages; the API Discovery service gives canonical method ids but no permissions. `iam-dataset`
is a convenience index over those same official surfaces, pinned by commit and cross-checked
against the curated official gRPC table, so the numbers are reproducible.

